  It took some doing for me to get around all the &quot;god stuff&quot; in the books <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  but the stories and characters are engaging.<br>
<br>
Anyroad, I find myself more and more puzzled by the characters' religiousness--or rather, perhaps, the expression of their beliefs.  Similarly, I am often puzzled by the role of Xianity in the south and these concepts--which I've only ever heard expressed south of the Mason-Dixon--that include, for instance, giving up control to god and leaving it all up to him and doing all they do--from their job to gardening--for god.  And in these books, I swear they stop and pray every five minutes!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
Completely aside from my current status as a non-believer (I was a Xian a lot longer than I've been a pagan UU, so it's not foreign to me), I think that being a dyed-in-the-wool Yankee has something to do with this disconnect in understanding.  I'm sure there are folks around here who share this kind of--is evangelicalism the right word?  But it's not pervasive in the culture here as it is down south.  I wonder if anyone has studied or explored this regional difference in Xian belief and understanding?  I'm so curious, especially since it appears to be playing a much more crucial role in national politics (read: McCain's victory in NH vs. Bush's victory in SC).<br>
<br>
